  "cells": [
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "stock-rationale",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Monte Carlo Simulation of Portfolio Risk\n",
        "\n",
        "### Introduction\n",
        "\n",
        "The future value of a portfolio is uncertain because asset prices change every day. Rather than trying to predict a single future outcome, Monte Carlo simulation can be used to generate many possible scenarios based on the portfolio's historical behavior.\n",
        "\n",
        "To test the accuracy of this method, this project is split into two distinct parts: building the predictive model using historical data, and then backtesting those simulations against real market outcomes."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "3044a34a",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Part 1: Historical Analysis & Risk Prediction\n",
        "\n",
        "The goal of this part is to estimate the probability that the portfolio loses money over a one-year period.\n",
        "\n",
        "To answer this question, I compare the final value of each simulated portfolio with the initial investment. The proportion of simulations that end below the initial value provides an estimate of the probability of a loss.\n",
        "\n",
        "This project serves as an introduction to Monte Carlo methods and demonstrates how simulation can be used to model uncertainty and quantify investment risk."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 129,
      "id": "initial_id",
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import seaborn as sns\n",
        "import yfinance as yf\n",
        "\n",
        "sns.set_theme(style=\"whitegrid\")"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 130,
      "id": "77aef6d7192bbb0",
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "HISTORY_PERIOD = \"1y\"\n",
        "\n",
        "apple_stock = yf.Ticker(\"AAPL\")\n",
        "cola_stock = yf.Ticker(\"KO\")\n",
        "\n",
        "apple_history = apple_stock.history(period=HISTORY_PERIOD)\n",
        "cola_history = cola_stock.history(period=HISTORY_PERIOD)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "ff6ee896",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Exploring daily returns\n",
        "\n",
        "Before running any simulations, it is helpful to visualize how each stock has moved day-to-day.\n",
        "\n",
        "Daily return = percentage change in the closing price from one day to the next.\n",
        "\n",
        "The plots below show two views for each stock:\n",
        "- Top row: returns over time — useful for spotting volatility and outliers\n",
        "- Bottom row: histogram of returns — shows the typical range and shape of daily moves\n",
        "\n",
        "These patterns are what I will later use to calibrate the Monte Carlo simulation."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 131,
      "id": "272d6c64",
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [
        {
          "data": {
            "image/png": "",
            "text/plain": [
              "<Figure size 1200x500 with 4 Axes>"
            ]
          },
          "metadata": {},
          "output_type": "display_data"
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "apple_returns = apple_history['Close'].pct_change().dropna()\n",
        "cola_returns = cola_history['Close'].pct_change().dropna()\n",
        "\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 5))  # Added figsize for better readability\n",
        "axes = ax.flatten()\n",
        "\n",
        "apple_returns.plot(ax=axes[0], title=\"Apple Daily Returns\", color=\"blue\")\n",
        "cola_returns.plot(ax=axes[1], title=\"Coca-Cola Daily Returns\", color=\"red\")\n",
        "sns.histplot(data = apple_returns, ax=axes[2], color=\"blue\")\n",
        "sns.histplot(data = cola_returns, ax=axes[3], color=\"red\")\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.tight_layout()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "cba3b26b",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Estimating Historical Return and Risk\n",
        "\n",
        "Before simulating future portfolio performance, I'll first estimate the historical characteristics of each asset.\n",
        "\n",
        "The mean daily return provides an estimate of the average daily growth rate observed during the historical period, while the standard deviation measures the variability of returns and serves as a proxy for risk.\n",
        "\n",
        "These statistics will be used as parameters for the probability distributions from which future returns are simulated."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 132,
      "id": "3ecf6df7",
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "Apple - Daily Mean: 0.00169, Volatility: 0.01425\n",
            "Coca-Cola - Daily Mean: 0.00074, Volatility: 0.01057\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "mean_apple = apple_returns.mean()\n",
        "mean_cola = cola_returns.mean()\n",
        "\n",
        "vol_apple = apple_returns.std()\n",
        "vol_cola = cola_returns.std()\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Apple - Daily Mean: {mean_apple:.5f}, Volatility: {vol_apple:.5f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Coca-Cola - Daily Mean: {mean_cola:.5f}, Volatility: {vol_cola:.5f}\")"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "6ffcfbdd",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Defining the Portfolio and Simulation Parameters\n",
        "\n",
        "To evaluate portfolio risk, I'll construct a portfolio consisting of 50% Apple and 50% Coca-Cola with an initial investment of $10,000.\n",
        "\n",
        "The simulation horizon is set to one trading year (252 trading days). To obtain a stable estimate of the probability of loss, 10,000 independent portfolio scenarios will be generated."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 133,
      "id": "440e7d27",
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "initial_investment = 10000\n",
        "weights = [0.5, 0.5]  \n",
        "t_days = 252\n",
        "simulations = 10000"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "834551cd",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Simulating Future Portfolio Outcomes\n",
        "\n",
        "Monte Carlo simulation works by generating many possible future scenarios using random sampling.\n",
        "\n",
        "For each asset, daily returns are sampled from a normal distribution parameterized by the historical mean return and historical volatility estimated earlier. This reflects the assumption that future returns will behave similarly to past returns.\n",
        "\n",
        "The simulated daily returns are compounded over time to create possible future price paths. Combining the simulated paths of both assets produces 10,000 possible trajectories for the portfolio over the next year."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 134,
      "id": "33664cae",
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "np.random.seed(42)\n",
        "\n",
        "random_shocks_apple = np.random.normal(loc=mean_apple, scale=vol_apple, size=(t_days, simulations))\n",
        "random_shocks_cola = np.random.normal(loc=mean_cola, scale=vol_cola, size=(t_days, simulations))\n",
        "\n",
        "apple_growth = 1 + random_shocks_apple\n",
        "cola_growth = 1 + random_shocks_cola\n",
        "\n",
        "apple_paths = np.cumprod(apple_growth, axis=0) * (initial_investment * weights[0])\n",
        "cola_paths = np.cumprod(cola_growth, axis=0) * (initial_investment * weights[1])\n",
        "\n",
        "portfolio_paths = apple_paths + cola_paths\n",
        "\n",
        "final_portfolio_values = portfolio_paths[-1, :]"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "e70c7279",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Statistical Inference and Risk Evaluation\n",
        "\n",
        "With 10,000 completed trials, I can transition from data generation to statistical inference. The goal is to convert these raw simulated endpoints into a single, actionable risk metric.\n",
        "\n",
        "To determine the probability of losing money, I'll apply a frequentist approach: counting every simulation where the final portfolio value fell below our initial \\$10,000 threshold and divide it by the total sample size \n",
        "\n",
        "I'll also calculate the Mean (Expected Value) and Median to evaluate the expected performance of the portfolio, alongside the minimum and maximum boundaries to understand the absolute extremes of the modeled risk."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 135,
      "id": "a1a971e7",
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "--- PROJECT RESULTS ---\n",
            "Probability of losing money over 1 year: 1.97%\n",
            "Number of scenarios resulting in a loss: 197 out of 10000\n",
            "-----------------------\n",
            "Average (Expected) Final Portfolio Value: $13,666.34\n",
            "Median Final Portfolio Value: $13,482.73\n",
            "Worst Simulated Outcome: $8,194.05\n",
            "Best Simulated Outcome: $24,603.74\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "losses = np.sum(final_portfolio_values < initial_investment)\n",
        "\n",
        "prob_of_loss = (losses / simulations) * 100\n",
        "\n",
        "expected_value = np.mean(final_portfolio_values)\n",
        "median_value = np.median(final_portfolio_values)\n",
        "worst_case = np.min(final_portfolio_values)\n",
        "best_case = np.max(final_portfolio_values)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"--- PROJECT RESULTS ---\")\n",
        "print(f\"Probability of losing money over 1 year: {prob_of_loss:.2f}%\")\n",
        "print(f\"Number of scenarios resulting in a loss: {losses} out of {simulations}\")\n",
        "print(f\"-----------------------\")\n",
        "print(f\"Average (Expected) Final Portfolio Value: ${expected_value:,.2f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Median Final Portfolio Value: ${median_value:,.2f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Worst Simulated Outcome: ${worst_case:,.2f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Best Simulated Outcome: ${best_case:,.2f}\")"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "93256d82",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Conclusion\n",
        "\n",
        "The objective of this project was to estimate the probability that a portfolio composed of 50% Apple and 50% Coca-Cola would lose money over a one-year investment horizon using Monte Carlo simulation.\n",
        "\n",
        "Based on 10000 simulated portfolio paths, the estimated probability of loss was 1.97%, corresponding to 197 loss scenarios out of 100 simulations. This suggests that, under the assumptions of the model and based on the historical data used, the portfolio had a relatively low likelihood of finishing the year below its initial value.\n",
        "\n",
        "The simulation produced an expected final portfolio value of \$36 13,666.34, while the median final value was \$3,482.73. The similarity between these two measures indicates that the distribution of outcomes was reasonably balanced, although some particularly strong positive scenarios increased the average outcome.\n",
        "\n",
        "The range of simulated results highlights the uncertainty inherent in financial markets. The worst simulated outcome resulted in a final portfolio value of $8,194.05, representing a substantial loss relative to the initial investment, while the best simulated outcome reached $24,603.74.\n",
        "\n",
        "Overall, the results illustrate how Monte Carlo simulation can be used to quantify investment risk and explore a range of possible future outcomes rather than relying on a single prediction. While the model relies on simplifying assumptions, it provides a practical framework for understanding uncertainty and estimating the probability of achieving specific investment objectives."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "5eead18f",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Part 2: Evaluating Monte Carlo Prediction Intervals\n",
        "\n",
        "## Introduction\n",
        "\n",
        "In the first part of this project, Monte Carlo simulation was used to estimate the probability that a portfolio would lose money over a one-year period. The simulation generated thousands of possible future outcomes based on historical returns and provided a probabilistic view of portfolio risk.\n",
        "\n",
        "This naturally leads to a new question:\n",
        "\n",
        "\"Can Monte Carlo simulations based on historical returns generate realistic prediction intervals for future stock prices?\"\n",
        "\n",
        "To investigate this question, I apply the same methodology to a selection of individual stocks. Historical data from one year is used to estimate the average return and volatility of each stock. These estimates are then used to simulate thousands of possible price paths for the following year.\n",
        "\n",
        "Unlike the portfolio analysis in Part 1, the goal here is not to estimate the probability of a gain or loss. Instead, the objective is to evaluate the quality of the Monte Carlo model by comparing its simulated outcomes with the stock prices that actually occurred.\n",
        "\n",
        "For each stock, a prediction interval will be constructed from the simulated results and compared with the realized stock price one year later. This allows us to assess whether the model produces realistic ranges of future outcomes and to better understand the strengths and limitations of this approach.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "bdee5b68",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Selecting Stocks\n",
        "\n",
        "To evaluate the Monte Carlo model across different types of companies, a small sample of stocks from various industries is selected.\n",
        "\n",
        "Including companies with different business models, market capitalizations, and volatility levels allows us to test whether the simulation performs consistently across different market conditions.\n",
        "\n",
        "The selected stocks are:\n",
        "\n",
        "* Apple (Technology)\n",
        "* Microsoft (Technology)\n",
        "* Coca-Cola (Consumer Staples)\n",
        "* JPMorgan Chase (Financial Services)\n",
        "* Exxon Mobil (Energy)\n",
        "* Walmart (Retail)"
      ]
    },
