      "source": [
        "returns = price_data.pct_change().dropna()\n",
        "\n",
        "mean_returns = returns.mean()\n",
        "volatility = returns.std()\n",
        "\n",
        "summary_stats = pd.DataFrame({\n",
        "    \"Mean Daily Return\": mean_returns,\n",
        "    \"Daily Volatility\": volatility\n",
        "})\n",
        "\n",
        "summary_stats"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "9b38ae10",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "The table above summarizes the historical return and risk characteristics of each stock during the training period.\n",
        "\n",
        "A higher mean return indicates stronger average historical performance, while a higher volatility indicates greater uncertainty in daily price movements.\n",
        "\n",
        "These statistics provide the foundation for the Monte Carlo model and represent the assumption that future returns will behave similarly to those observed in the historical data.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "33e8ef8a",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Correlation Between Assets\n",
        "\n",
        "In addition to return and volatility, it is useful to examine the relationship between the selected stocks.\n",
        "\n",
        "The correlation matrix measures the extent to which pairs of stocks tend to move together. Values close to 1 indicate strong positive relationships, while values near 0 indicate weaker relationships.\n",
        "\n",
        "Understanding these relationships is particularly important in portfolio analysis, where diversification depends on combining assets that do not move identically.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 140,
      "id": "37321367",
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [
        {
          "data": {
            "image/png": "",
            "text/plain": [
              "<Figure size 800x600 with 2 Axes>"
            ]
          },
          "metadata": {},
          "output_type": "display_data"
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "import seaborn as sns\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))\n",
        "\n",
        "sns.heatmap(\n",
        "    returns.corr(),\n",
        "    annot=True,\n",
        "    cmap=\"coolwarm\",\n",
        "    center=0\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.title(\"Correlation Matrix of Daily Returns\")\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "f946f8a4",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Correlation Results Analysis\n",
        "The matrix shows weak to moderate relationships across the stocks, which is ideal for a diversified portfolio.\n",
        "\n",
        "The strongest connection is between MSFT and AAPL (0.48), which makes sense since both are tech companies.\n",
        "\n",
        "Most other pairs have very low correlations (below 0.25). For example, AAPL and XOM sit at just 0.03, meaning they move almost entirely independently.\n",
        "\n",
        "Overall, these low and negative correlations mean the assets do not move in lockstep, which will help lower the portfolio's total risk during the simulation phase."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "3c4346c4",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Simulating Future Stock Prices\n",
        "\n",
        "Using the historical mean return and volatility estimated in the previous section, Monte Carlo simulation is used to generate possible future price paths for each stock.\n",
        "\n",
        "For every company, 10,000 independent simulations are performed over a one-year horizon (252 trading days). Each simulated daily return is randomly sampled from a normal distribution parameterized by the stock's historical mean return and volatility.\n",
        "\n",
        "The result is a distribution of possible future prices rather than a single prediction. This allows us to construct prediction intervals and assess whether the realized stock prices fall within the range of outcomes generated by the model.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 141,
      "id": "e281e948",
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "simulation_days = 252\n",
        "n_simulations = 10000\n",
        "\n",
        "np.random.seed(42)\n",
        "\n",
        "simulation_results = {}\n",
        "\n",
        "for stock in price_data.columns:\n",
        "\n",
        "    mu = mean_returns[stock]\n",
        "    sigma = volatility[stock]\n",
        "\n",
        "    initial_price = price_data[stock].iloc[-1]\n",
        "\n",
        "    simulated_returns = np.random.normal(\n",
        "        loc=mu,\n",
        "        scale=sigma,\n",
        "        size=(simulation_days, n_simulations)\n",
        "    )\n",
        "\n",
        "    growth_factors = 1 + simulated_returns\n",
        "\n",
        "    price_paths = np.cumprod(\n",
        "        growth_factors,\n",
        "        axis=0\n",
        "    ) * initial_price\n",
        "\n",
        "    simulation_results[stock] = price_paths"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "43263374",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "To better understand the behavior of the simulation model, it is useful to visualize a sample of the generated price paths.\n",
        "\n",
        "The figure below displays a subset of simulated trajectories for one stock. Each line represents a possible future evolution generated by the model.\n",
        "\n",
        "Together, these paths illustrate the uncertainty associated with future stock performance and show how a range of outcomes can emerge from the same historical data.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 142,
      "id": "6976f8ca",
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [
