      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Discussion\n",
        "\n",
        "The coverage rate provides a simple measure of how well the Monte Carlo model captured the realized stock prices.\n",
        "\n",
        "A high coverage rate suggests that the intervals generated from historical mean returns and volatility were broad enough to encompass most realized outcomes. Conversely, stocks that fell outside the prediction intervals indicate situations where the model underestimated or overestimated future uncertainty.\n",
        "\n",
        "It is important to note that the objective of this study was not to predict the exact future price of each stock. Rather, the goal was to evaluate whether a simple Monte Carlo model could generate realistic ranges of future outcomes using only historical information.\n",
        "\n",
        "The results provide insight into both the usefulness and the limitations of simulation-based forecasting in financial markets.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "3f77b789",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Beyond Prediction Intervals\n",
        "\n",
        "Although all realized stock prices fell within the 5th–95th percentile prediction intervals, these intervals were often quite wide. While this suggests that the model successfully captured the realized outcomes, wide intervals may provide limited practical value for investors seeking precise forecasts.\n",
        "\n",
        "To better understand the model's performance, the percentile rank of each realized stock price within its simulated distribution was calculated. This allows us to evaluate not only whether the realized outcome was captured, but also how typical or unusual it was according to the model."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "519b0fec",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Calculating Percentile Ranks\n",
        "\n",
        "The prediction intervals provide a binary evaluation: either the realized stock price falls within the interval or it does not.\n",
        "\n",
        "However, this approach does not indicate where the realized price falls within the simulated distribution.\n",
        "\n",
        "To obtain a more detailed assessment, the percentile rank of each realized stock price is calculated. The percentile rank represents the proportion of simulated outcomes that are less than or equal to the realized value.\n",
        "\n",
        "For example, a percentile rank of 50% indicates that the realized price is near the center of the simulated distribution, while a percentile rank of 95% indicates that the realized outcome was higher than 95% of the simulated scenarios.\n",
        "\n",
        "This allows me to determine whether the realized stock prices were typical outcomes according to the model or whether they occurred near the extremes of the simulated distribution.\n"
      ]
    },
